00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:08.080
in the Army at one point.

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:14.150
And then of course, the rubber
band was wrapped around a football.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:20.080
And the role of the artist
is to actually build a world,

00:18:20.080 --> 00:18:23.630
to build sort of a visual
world for the readers.

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:24.930
And you'll notice next

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:29.940
to the football might be a
trophy, a football trophy.

00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:32.540
So I'm letting you in on something

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:35.420
or I'm actually letting
you read the pictures.

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:39.240
So not only is it a search
and find, but it also deals

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:41.880
with the life of this grandfather.

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:43.850
So it goes on, of course.

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:50.230 position:56%
Then you have the -- trying to think
of the order of the paintbrush,

00:18:50.230 --> 00:18:57.090
which was that we get a sense that
the grandmother was a painter.

00:18:57.090 --> 00:18:59.000
And that's, of course,
of value to him.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:00.300
So it goes on.

00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:01.600
Of course, the lemon drop.

00:19:01.600 --> 00:19:03.280
Who could resist a
lemon drop, right?

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:06.980
Exactly. So that's
in a box of marbles.

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:10.200 position:56%
Now, how did I decide about marbles?

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:13.690
Because when I was a kid
I loved playing marbles.

00:19:13.690 --> 00:19:16.530
And so that you can see not only

00:19:16.530 --> 00:19:23.470
in my illustrations working towards
speaking to the story itself,

00:19:23.470 --> 00:19:26.300
the text itself, but
we're also giving --

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:29.190
I'm giving you a part of my life.

00:19:29.190 --> 00:19:32.230
Now, if you guys venture
into buying the book,

00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:35.360
I want you to look under the cover.

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:42.490
You guys, underneath the
cover -- you can't see it now.

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:44.900
So that means you really
have to buy the book.

00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:50.240
But the case cover, it's not
only the objects that you find

00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:54.350
in the book that the grandpa hides,

00:19:54.350 --> 00:20:00.200
but also on the case cover are the
tools that I used to make the book.

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:05.860
So you'll find in this illustration
pencils that I used, pastels,

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:08.690
of course, water colors,
and pencils.

00:20:08.690 --> 00:20:13.040
Now, pencils is the
really the instrument

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:15.310
or the drawing tool of choice.

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:19.250
And a little story about that
because I had an interview earlier.

00:20:19.250 --> 00:20:22.330
And we were talking about
the love of drawing.

00:20:22.330 --> 00:20:25.490
And I said, "You know what's
so cool about all this?"

00:20:25.490 --> 00:20:27.120
I was just thinking about this.

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:31.060
I said, "If you read about me,
and I write a lot of pieces,

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:38.470 position:56%
essays on my process, and the medium
is pencil and water color on paper."

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:44.500
Okay. So I write a lot about the
fact that, again, that tool --

00:20:44.500 --> 00:20:49.360
instrument of choice -- to help
me make marks is the pencil.

00:20:49.360 --> 00:20:53.850
Now, here's the thing
that I just thought about.

00:20:53.850 --> 00:20:58.230 position:56%
When I was a kid growing up, I
didn't have access to art materials.

00:20:58.230 --> 00:21:05.670
My parents weren't museum
or gallery visitors at all.

00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:12.540 position:56%
They didn't have a cool
understanding of what an artist was.

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:16.900
What's interesting is although they
supported their young son's need

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:21.250
to draw, so I always
had materials at hand.

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:23.910
Here's the cool part.

00:21:23.910 --> 00:21:27.240
I grew up on a very small street

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:29.880
in the Germantown section
of Philadelphia.

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:33.450
All of the neighbors
were African-Americans

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.350
who migrated south.

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:38.930
Outside of that world were
Jewish and Italian communities.

00:21:38.930 --> 00:21:43.190
So in the '40s we were
somewhat isolated.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:48.190
In order to keep the young boys
somewhat busy in a positive way,

00:21:48.190 --> 00:21:50.650
we were encouraged to draw.

00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:55.770
And my parents didn't have a sense
about what art might lead to,

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:58.460
but the boys were actually
encouraged to draw

00:21:58.460 --> 00:22:00.840
as a positive way to use that time.

00:22:00.840 --> 00:22:07.330
I'm going to go back to the fact
that the pencil as instrument

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:10.960
of choice on that block
of row homes,

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:14.480
and the end of that block
there was a factory.

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:18.030
The factory was a pencil factory.

00:22:18.030 --> 00:22:22.230
And my grandfather
worked in the factory.

00:22:22.230 --> 00:22:26.200
And he would bring
home lots of pencils.

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:30.830
So here's the thing about being an
artist for you parents out there

00:22:30.830 --> 00:22:35.260
and grandparents that might have
children that are interested

00:22:35.260 --> 00:22:41.610
in drawing -- that
key piece that started

00:22:41.610 --> 00:22:45.710
when I was a very young child,
the fashion and the love

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:49.440
for making a mark and then
making a mark with the pencil.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:54.140
And that has stayed with me over
the course of some almost --

00:22:54.140 --> 00:22:58.830 position:56%
my first book was published in 1964.

00:22:58.830 --> 00:23:02.800
It was done in pencil
with color washes.

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:06.170
And today when I get up in the
morning and most days when I get

00:23:06.170 --> 00:23:09.080
up in the morning and
I walk to the studio,

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:15.140
I sit down at my drawing board,
and most often I pick up a pencil.

00:23:15.140 --> 00:23:18.090
Thank you, Grandfather Charles.

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:19.700
Thank you, guys.

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:21.510
Well appreciated.

00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:26.040
[ Applause ]

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:27.640
All right.

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:28.940
I think that's it.

00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:30.240
Our time's up, right?

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:31.540
I have two minutes.

00:23:31.540 --> 00:23:35.140
Do I have two minutes if there's
a question in the audience?

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:37.510
Yes?

00:23:37.510 --> 00:23:43.530
